@page "/composition"

<Styled @bind-Classname="@grey">
    label: white;
    background-color: white;
</Styled>

<Styled @bind-Classname="@bigFont">
    label: big-font;
    font-size: 32px;
</Styled>

<Styled @bind-Classname="@div" Compose1="@grey" Compose2="@bigFont" Compose2If="@_showBig" />

<h1>Class Composition</h1>

<p><code>&lt;Styled /></code> allows you to compose multipile classes into one class. Let's begin with an example:</p>

<div class="@div">
    Some text
</div>

<button @onclick="@onclick">Toggle Font Size</button>

<PrettyCode CodeFile="_content/SampleCore/compose1.html" HighlightLines="11" />

<p>The highlighted line shows how to compone css classes. First, define the classes you plan to use. This is done in lines 1-9. Compose them together using the attribute
    <code>Compose[any string here]</code>. You may compose any number of classes together.</p>

<h3>Conditional Class Composition</h3>

<p>In the example above, the class for <code>@@bigFont</code> only gets applied when the button is clicked. 
    Adding a <code>bool</code> attribute named <code>Compose[same string here]If</code>, will apply a class only when the value is true. In this example,
    that is done with when <code>Compose2If="@@_showBig"</code> the corresponding class: <code>Compose2="@@bigFont"</code> gets applied.
    </p>

@code {
    private string div, grey, bigFont;
    private bool _showBig = false;

    private void onclick()
    {
        _showBig = !_showBig;
    }
}